  "stage": {
    "id": "building_daos",
    "stageNumber": 5,
    "title": "DAO Building Strategies",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "decentralized_org_barriers",
        "title": "Key Barriers for Decentralized Organizations",
        "content": "## Barrier 1: Decentralized Decision-Making is Hard\n\nThere are no governance best practices yet. Bitcoin's fully decentralized governance is suitable for a **value storage protocol that needs almost no changes**.\n\nBut it's not suitable for early technology projects that need rapid iteration.\n\n> **Some centralized decision-making is needed initially**, with design aiming for decentralization long-term.\n\n## Barrier 2: Difficulty Measuring Contributions\n\nBitcoin mining contributions are objectively measured and hard to game. It's clear who provided how much hash power.\n\nBut **most labor types are difficult to accurately measure contribution**:\n\n- Marketing campaign effectiveness?\n- Design improvement value?\n- Community management contribution?\n\nCentralized human judgment is often needed for resource allocation.\n\n## Barrier 3: Misuse and Ambiguity of 'Decentralization'\n\n- Some consider **everything except Bitcoin centralized** (extreme maximalism)\n- Others **disguise centralized ICOs as decentralized organizations** (fraudulent marketing)\n\nAs \"decentralization\" became misused as a marketing term, what's actually decentralized became unclear.",
        "position": {
          "x": 3,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "progressive_decentralization",
        "title": "Progressive Decentralization Strategy",
        "content": "## a16z's Playbook\n\n**Jesse Walden** (a16z crypto) presented three components of crypto success in his 2020 \"Progressive Decentralization.\"\n\n### Stage 1: Product/Market Fit (PMF)\n\n**Don't pretend to be decentralized at this stage.**\n\n- Core team leads all product decisions\n- Hold admin privileges over smart contracts\n- **No token launch**: Reliance on core team effort risks meeting Howey Test securities classification criteria\n\nIf early users complain about core team control, it's actually a **good sign**. But transparency about control's existence is essential.\n\n### Stage 2: Community Participation\n\nWhen early traction signals appear (growing user base, developer ecosystem), it's time to invest in community harmony.\n\n- **Technical constraints**: Compound v2.2's 48-hour waiting period (gives escape time)\n- **Introduce fees**: After strong network effects form\n- **Test token distribution**: First to a permissioned group\n\n### Stage 3: Sufficient Decentralization\n\nThe final stage after achieving PMF, strong community, and sustainable incentive model.\n\nTeam \"exits to community\" through **broad token distribution**.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "howey_test",
        "title": "Howey Test and Securities Classification",
        "content": "## What is the Howey Test?\n\nCriteria from a 1946 US Supreme Court case for determining whether an asset is a **security**.\n\n| Requirement | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| ① Investment of money (value)? | Did you pay money to buy the token? |\n| ② Common enterprise? | Is that money used for a joint project? |\n| ③ Expectation of profits? | Do you expect token price to rise? |\n| ④ Reliance on others' efforts? | Does profit come from others' (team, founders) efforts? |\n\n**If all four apply → Likely classified as a security.**\n\n## Applied to Crypto\n\nIn ICOs or token sales, if buyers expected \"token price will rise if the founding team works hard,\" requirement ④ is met. In this case, the token is classified as a security and becomes subject to SEC regulation.\n\n## Why 'Sufficient Decentralization' is the Solution\n\nIf the protocol operates autonomously without a team:\n\n> No longer \"relying on others' (team) efforts\" → Requirement ④ not met → **May not be a security**\n\nThis is the basis for a16z presenting \"progressive decentralization\" as a regulatory compliance strategy.\n\n## Real Cases\n\n| Project | Result |\n|---------|--------|\n| Kik (KIN token) | SEC lawsuit → $5M fine (2020) |\n| Ripple (XRP) | SEC lawsuit → Partial win in 2023 (exchange sales = non-security, institutional sales = security) |\n| Ethereum | SEC essentially recognized \"currently decentralized, therefore not a security\" |",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "exit_to_community",
        "title": "Exit to Community",
        "content": "## What is Exit to Community?\n\nTraditional startup exits are **IPO (Initial Public Offering)** or **M&A (Merger & Acquisition)**. Founders and investors sell their shares and leave.\n\nDAO's new exit strategy is **Exit to Community**:\n\n> Team \"exits to community\" — Airdrops tokens to users and contributors according to a predetermined plan\n\n## What's Achieved\n\n### 1. Platform Risk Removal\n\nCore team transfers majority ownership (fees, control) of the application. Team can no longer change rules at will.\n\n### 2. Token Transition to Non-Security\n\nSufficient decentralization can avoid Howey Test's \"reliance on others' efforts\" requirement.\n\n### 3. Cooperative Economic Model\n\nUser-owners realize **increasing returns through cooperative economic model**. Platform growth directly returns to users.\n\n## Success Cases (2026)\n\n| Project | Token | Description |\n|---------|-------|-------------|\n| Uniswap | UNI | Large-scale airdrop to users in September 2020 |\n| Compound | COMP | Pioneer of DeFi governance tokens |\n| Optimism | OP | Airdrop to L2 users |\n| Arbitrum | ARB | Largest L2 airdrop in 2023 |\n\nHowever, legal standards for 'sufficient decentralization' remain unclear as of 2026.",
        "position": {
          "x": 15,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
